# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler Process Methodology
# Process patterns: how to debug compiler issues, how to scope
# slot work, how to verify slot premises, how to triage cross-
# repo bug reports. Earn their slot when an agent is starting a
# slot, debugging a regression, or scoping a fix.
#
# For design / convention patterns see patterns.cyml.
# For non-obvious internal traps see gotchas.cyml.
#
# 10 entries (.63 added: real-flow gate vs self-host placebo).

[[entries]]
name = "premise_check_at_slot_entry"
description = "Read the actual code + run a 5-line probe BEFORE adopting a pin's stated scope. Three out of six slots in the v5.8.x slices sub-arc had pin premises that were empirically wrong."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["process", "scoping", "v5.7.x", "v5.8.x"]
content = """
**The rule**: when starting a slot, the pin describes intended
scope based on what the previous slot's author thought was true.
Empirically, those assumptions are wrong often enough that a
5-line probe at slot entry is the highest-value 5 minutes of
the slot.

**Probe shape**: write the smallest possible cyrius source that
exercises what the pin assumes works. Compile + run. Observe.

**Examples from v5.8.x** (the discipline earned its keep across
the sub-arc):

§7 (v5.8.15) pin assumed slice indexing was straightforward —
just lower `s[i]` to a bounds-checked load. Probe: write
`var s1: [u8] = 0; var s2: [u8] = 0; slice_set(&s1, ...);
slice_set(&s2, ...);`. Crashed. Found a pre-existing 16-byte
fn-local slot-collision bug (silent since v5.5 because no tcyr
exercised adjacent fn-local slices). §7 scope expanded honestly
to "indexing + layout-fix in one slot."

§8 (v5.8.16) pin assumed dot-syntax was straightforward. Probe:
`var s: [u8] = 0; slice_set(...); s.len = 3; var n = s.len;`.
Read 0 instead of 3. Found regalloc post-body peephole was
patching the high-half slot's EFLSTORE to a register move,
leaving the stack slot uninitialized. Plus the layout-flip
exposed a pre-existing tail-call escape bug. §8 scope expanded
honestly to "dot-syntax + address-based field I/O + tail-call
escape skip."

§9 (v5.8.17) pin assumed `s.data` / `s.len` already worked on
Str-typed locals and §9 was just a stdlib migration. Probe:
`var s: Str = str_from("hello"); return s.len;`. Returned 0.
Found PARSE_FIELD_LOAD's struct-typed-local branch always used
inline-mode addressing, but heap-alloc'd Str pointers store a
pointer in a single slot. §9 scope FLIPPED — capability had
to ship first; mass migration moved to §10.

**Anti-pattern** (the alternative: skip the probe, commit to
the pin's framing, hit a wall mid-slot, defer half the work
to "next slot" without filing where): see anti-patterns.cyml's
`scope_cut_mid_slot` entry. Ballooned v5.6.x's deferment rate;
v5.7.x discipline + v5.8.x sub-arc's three premise-flips
explicitly avoided that trajectory.

**When the probe passes**: still a valuable 5 minutes — confirms
the slot's foundation. The probe + a quick assertion in a
.tcyr regression run becomes the slot's `step 0` tests.

Cross-ref: methodology.cyml's `attribute_regressions_to_platform_drift`
(verify the FRAMING of "regression" pins before investing).

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `premise_check_at_slot_entry_v58x`
+ feedback memory `feedback_premise_check_at_slot_entry`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "perf_test_dont_assume_correctness_isnt_perf"
description = "Correctness tests are not performance tests. Add benchmarks BEFORE shipping an optimization. Global taxes never pay for local wins."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["performance", "optimization", "regression", "v3.3.5"]
content = """
**The rule**: when shipping a codegen change labeled as an
optimization, write the benchmark FIRST. The .bcyr harness
exists for exactly this reason. Correctness tests passing
(self-host byte-identical, full .tcyr suite green) is
NECESSARY but NOT SUFFICIENT — a perf regression is silent on
those gates.

**Two related rules**:

1. **Global taxes never pay for local wins.** If your "speedup
   for hot loops" adds overhead to every function call (extra
   prologue/epilogue, stack frame shift), the tax bill exceeds
   the savings unless the optimization is gated per-function.
   `#regalloc 1` directive style — opt-in, per-fn — is correct;
   "every fn always pays the cost" is wrong.

2. **Silent fallback is dangerous.** If your optimization can
   regress correctness on a code shape it doesn't recognize,
   either fix it to be safe across all shapes OR refuse to
   compile that shape. NEVER silently produce wrong code on
   inputs your peephole pattern doesn't match.

**Concrete example** (v3.3.5 r12 loop-var cache regression):

Cached the loop counter in r12 to avoid stack reload every
iteration. Tests passed; self-host byte-identical. Then
cyrius-doom benchmarks caught it:

  render_frame:  2.2ms → 4.3ms   (2x slower)
  fixed_mul:     435ns → 662ns   (1.5x slower)

Why: every fn call paid `push r12 / pop r12` to preserve the
caller's r12 value across the call. The cost on every caller
exceeded the savings on the optimized loops. Plus the frame
shift (rsp prologue change to make room for r12 save) silently
broke 7+ arg functions — they read garbage for the 7th arg
because stack-arg offsets shifted from `[rbp+16]` to `[rbp+24]`.
Bug #32 (silent miscompile) and the 2x perf regression were
the SAME underlying change.

Reverted at v3.3.12. Dead accessors sat in util.cyr until
v3.4.16 closeout cleaned them up.

**The right shape** (eventually delivered at v5.6.20+): per-fn
register allocation via Poletto-Sarkar linear-scan picker.
Auto-enabled via picker for fns that benefit; opt-out via
`#regalloc 0`; safety scan abort if the picker hits an unsafe
shape (asm + regalloc, &local taken, etc.).

**Generalize to**: any codegen change. ALWAYS pair with a
.bcyr that measures the workload the optimization targets.
Compare pre/post on a real consumer (cyrius-doom, sigil PQC,
sankoch encode/decode) to verify the win is real and the tax
is bounded.

Full backstory: retros/v3.cyml `r12_loop_var_regression_lesson`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "verify_outputs_not_just_exit_codes"
description = "sed/grep returning 0 doesn't mean it changed anything. Diff the file or re-read the value to confirm. Exact-match sed is fragile; permissive regex + verification > strict-match + || true."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["release-process", "scripts", "v3.4.16", "v5.6.39"]
content = """
**The rule**: a successful exit code from sed / grep / awk /
any data-mutating script does NOT mean the script changed what
you expected. ALWAYS verify the OUTPUT — diff the file, re-read
the literal, hash the result.

**Two related anti-patterns**:

1. **`|| true` swallowing failures**. Convenient until it
   hides silent data corruption. Prefer explicit error
   handling — detect no-match, warn, continue (or fail).

2. **Exact-match sed**. When you sed-replace a literal, ANY
   drift makes the replacement a no-op. Use permissive regexes
   that tolerate drift AND validate the result.

**Two cyrius examples**:

v3.4.10–v3.4.16: `cc3 --version` reported `cc3 3.4.10` for 5
releases because the bump script's exact-match sed silently
failed. Users filed bugs with stale version output.
Diagnosis: `./build/cc3 --version | od -c` — 30 seconds of
bytewise inspection found it.

v5.6.29-1 → v5.6.38: same shape recurred (9 releases of stale
version output). Fix at v5.6.39 routed the version through
generated source (see patterns.cyml's
`version_string_via_generated_source_not_hardcoded`) so the
bump script no longer rewrites `src/main.cyr` directly.

**The right release-process shape**:

```sh
# OLD (fragile):
sed -i "s/\"cc3 $OLD/\"cc3 $NEW/" src/main.cyr 2>/dev/null || true

# BETTER:
if ! sed -i -E "s|\"cc3 [0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\\\n\"|\"cc3 $NEW\\\\n\"|" src/main.cyr; then
    echo "ERROR: sed failed" >&2
    exit 1
fi
# Verify:
if ! grep -q "\"cc3 $NEW\\\\n\"" src/main.cyr; then
    echo "ERROR: post-sed source doesn't contain expected version" >&2
    exit 1
fi

# BEST (the v5.6.39 shape):
# Don't sed source at all — generate src/version_str.cyr from
# the bump script and have src/main.cyr include it.
cat > src/version_str.cyr <<EOF
var _VERSION_STR = "cycc ${NEW}\\n";
var _VERSION_LEN = $((${#NEW} + 5));
EOF
# Then verify by running the binary:
if [ "$(./build/cycc --version)" != "cycc $NEW" ]; then
    echo "ERROR: --version output mismatch" >&2
    exit 1
fi
```

**Generalize**: any release-process step that mutates source +
relies on regex matching needs a corresponding verification
step. The build IS the product; verifying the build's
correctness is a first-class release deliverable.

Full backstory: retros/v3.cyml `version_string_silent_drift`
+ patterns.cyml `version_string_via_generated_source_not_hardcoded`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "verify_slot_premise_before_investing"
description = "When a slot is initially pinned as 'platform drift' or 'compiler regression', verify the framing FIRST. Reproduce the failure + inspect the failing artifact (otool/objdump/xxd) BEFORE adopting the suspect list."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["debugging", "regression-triage", "v5.6.33", "v5.6.36"]
content = """
**The rule**: when a roadmap slot is pinned as "platform X
regressed" or "arch Y broke," the pin is the AUTHOR'S best
guess about WHERE the bug lives — not the actual diagnosis.
Before investing in the suspect list, reproduce the failure +
inspect the failing artifact directly.

**The cyrius example**: v5.6.33 (Mach-O) and v5.6.36 (PE) were
two consecutive "platform drift" regression pins on the cyrius
roadmap. Both turned out to be the SAME test-fixture bug — a
fn named `main` in a tcyr that the runner's auto-discover
treated specially on platforms whose entry-point convention
differed.

Neither was a compiler regression. Both pins suggested
investigating Mach-O LC_DYLD_INFO_ONLY emission and PE
.reloc generation respectively. Both directions were wrong.

**The diagnostic that would have saved the time**:

```sh
# Reproduce on the platform:
./build/cycc_macho_arm < failing_test.cyr > /tmp/fail
otool -tv /tmp/fail   # disassemble the fail
xxd /tmp/fail | head  # inspect the bytes

# Compare to a passing test:
./build/cycc_macho_arm < passing_test.cyr > /tmp/pass
otool -tv /tmp/pass
diff <(otool -tv /tmp/fail) <(otool -tv /tmp/pass)
```

Within minutes the diff would have shown that the differing
bytes were a fn label / symbol issue, not a relocation issue.
The pin's framing pointed at the wrong layer.

**Generalize**: for any slot pinned as "regression in X":

1. Reproduce on the platform.
2. Inspect the failing artifact (`otool -tv` for Mach-O,
   `objdump -d` for ELF, `xxd` for raw bytes).
3. Compare to a passing build.
4. ONLY THEN read the pin's suspect list — and treat it as
   one hypothesis among several.

**Anti-pattern**: starting from the pin's suspect list and
spending hours instrumenting LC_DYLD_INFO_ONLY emission code
that turns out to be unchanged across the regression. The
pin's author wasn't malicious — they wrote the best framing
they could from the symptom they observed. But the symptom is
not the diagnosis.

Cross-ref: methodology.cyml's `premise_check_at_slot_entry`
(read code + probe BEFORE adopting scope). Same shape — verify
the foundation before building.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's
`two_consecutive_platform_drift_pins_were_both_fn_main_fixture_bugs`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "triage_dep_boundary_per_row_checksum"
description = "When a downstream consumer reports 'X corrupts at scale' and the suspect crosses a dep boundary (cyrius compiler / sankoch encoder / patra page allocator), instrument both sides of the boundary with per-row checksums. Standalone replay of dumped buffers + in-process roundtrip + per-row checksum localizes the corruption."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["debugging", "cross-repo", "triage", "v5.6.35"]
content = """
**The rule**: cross-repo bug reports of the shape "X works
fine for small inputs, corrupts at scale" usually have a
specific tipping point. The triage methodology is:

1. **Standalone replay of dumped buffers.** Get the actual
   buffer bytes from the failing run; try to re-run the
   suspect operation outside the consumer.

2. **In-process roundtrip instrumentation.** Add per-row
   checksums (CRC32 / SHA-1 / even XOR-hash) at every
   suspected stage. Encode → decode → compare per-row.

3. **Per-row checksum at each dep boundary.** When the data
   flows compiler → sankoch encoder → patra page allocator →
   sankoch decoder → consumer reader, instrument BOTH SIDES
   of each boundary. The corruption shows up as the first row
   where pre-boundary checksum != post-boundary checksum.

**The cyrius example** (v5.6.35): sit's "fsck reports unreadable
objects at scale" pin was filed against cyrius. Initial
suspicion: `alloc()` corruption (sit's blob layer was a
plausible victim of a heap regression).

Triage applied:

1. Dumped the failing blob from sit's WAL → standalone
   sankoch replay outside sit.
2. Added per-row checksums INSIDE sankoch's encode loop +
   decode loop.
3. Found checksum drift in the encoder's deflate output.
   First mismatch was at row N=128k; pre-deflate checksum was
   stable, post-deflate checksum diverged.

Conclusion: not a cyrius bug. Sankoch's deflate encoder had a
buffer-aliasing bug that was masked at small scale (deflate
output buffer < input buffer almost always; corruption only
when a specific bit pattern caused the encoder's literal-vs-
ref decision to land on a stale offset). Filed as a sankoch
issue; cyrius pin closed.

**Generalize**: any cross-repo "corrupts at scale" should
START with this methodology. Cyrius gets blamed often (it's
the language layer; everything routes through it); the actual
bug is usually one layer higher in a dep. Fast triage saves
days of misattributed compiler-internal investigation.

**The instrumentation pattern**:

```cyr
# Encoder side (sankoch):
fn encode_row(row_buf, row_len) {
    var pre_checksum = sha1_hash(row_buf, row_len);
    var enc = deflate_encode(row_buf, row_len);
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2, "row pre=", 8); print_hex(pre_checksum);
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2, " post=", 6); print_hex(sha1_hash(enc.data, enc.len));
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2, "\\n", 1);
    return enc;
}

# Decoder side (sankoch consumer):
fn decode_row(enc_buf, enc_len) {
    var dec = deflate_decode(enc_buf, enc_len);
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2, "row dec=", 8); print_hex(sha1_hash(dec.data, dec.len));
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2, "\\n", 1);
    return dec;
}
```

Run both sides with the failing fixture. The first row where
encoder's `post=X` != decoder's `dec=X` is the corruption
boundary.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's
`sit_symptom_2_was_sankoch_encoder_not_cyrius`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ci_drift_detection_silent_skip_is_false_green"
description = "Silent SKIP in CI gates is False-PASS in disguise. Every gate must report PASS / FAIL / SKIP explicitly, and SKIP must be a known-acceptable state, not 'binary not built so we'll just continue.'"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ci", "regression-prevention", "v5.7.36", "v5.7.50"]
content = """
**The rule**: in any CI gate that can be skipped (binary not
built, dep not available, platform not supported), the SKIP
must be EXPLICIT and KNOWN-ACCEPTABLE. A gate that silently
returns 0 when it can't run is reporting False-PASS.

**The two cyrius regressions caused by this**:

v5.7.29: `check.sh` had `set -e` AT THE TOP, which made any
non-zero exit abort the script entirely. A failing gate
mid-script aborted the whole run + the FINAL pass-count print
was never reached → CI saw "no output, exit 0" and reported
green. Latent for an unknown duration; user-surfaced when a
deliberate mid-script failure didn't bubble up to red.

Fix at v5.7.29: removed `set -e`; replaced with explicit gate-
level checks. Each gate prints `PASS:` / `FAIL:` / `SKIP:` and
the final tally line counts each.

v5.7.36 + v5.7.50: format/lint gates checked for cyrfmt /
cyrlint binaries via `[ -x "$ROOT/build/cyrfmt" ]` and SILENTLY
returned 0 if missing. So a fresh-install failure (binary not
built) reported PASS.

Fix at v5.7.36: print `SKIP: cyrfmt not built` explicitly, and
the gate counts SKIP separately from PASS in the tally line.
Final state: a green check.sh with N gates SKIPPED is
distinguishable from a green check.sh with N gates PASSED.

v5.8.18 (current): the api-surface gate has been silently
skipping since v5.7.50 because the binary isn't auto-built
(see roadmap.md v5.8.42 pin). The gate prints `skip: not
built` and exits 0. v5.8.42 will fix the binary auto-build +
re-enable the gate as a PASS-or-FAIL, not skip.

**The right gate shape**:

```sh
# Bad — silent skip:
if [ ! -x "$ROOT/build/cyrfmt" ]; then exit 0; fi
"$ROOT/build/cyrfmt" --check src/...
# (returns 0 in either case; CI can't tell built-and-passed
#  from not-built-and-skipped)

# Better — explicit + counted:
if [ ! -x "$ROOT/build/cyrfmt" ]; then
    echo "  SKIP: $ROOT/build/cyrfmt not built"
    exit 0
fi
"$ROOT/build/cyrfmt" --check src/...
rc=$?
if [ "$rc" -eq 0 ]; then echo "  PASS"; else echo "  FAIL"; fi
exit $rc

# Best — failed-skip is a hard error after first ship:
# Once a binary has shipped in [release].bins, missing-binary
# is a regression, NOT acceptable skip. Promote SKIP → FAIL
# after the first release that includes the binary.
```

**Generalize**: every CI gate's exit code should be one of
PASS / FAIL / KNOWN-SKIP. A KNOWN-SKIP must have a documented
reason that's tracked toward resolution. Anything else is
False-PASS until proven otherwise.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's
`audit_silent_skip_is_false_green_v5_7_36` +
`auto_deps_gate_inflates_self_host_size_v5_7_38`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ci_drift_detection_orphaned_path_is_certain_drift"
description = "Code paths with no CI gate accumulate silent drift. The cyrius-x bytecode entry (main_cx.cyr) accumulated 4+ silent-drift breakages across v5.6.x + v5.7.x because no CI ever built it. Add a gate before working on a backend, not after."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ci", "backend", "drift-prevention", "v5.7.11"]
content = """
**The rule**: any code path that doesn't have a CI gate WILL
accumulate silent drift. Not "might" — WILL. The drift
accumulates at exactly the rate at which surrounding code
changes; for a cyrius backend (frontend changes ripple through
each backend), that's every few patches.

**The cyrius example**: `src/main_cx.cyr` (the cyrius-x
bytecode entry point) accumulated 4+ silent breakages across
v5.6.x + v5.7.x because no CI ever built it:

1. Missing `include "common/ir.cyr"` after IR was added in
   v5.6.x — main_cx.cyr never picked it up.
2. Missing globals for new-since-v5.6 IR helpers: `_AARCH64_BACKEND`,
   `_TARGET_MACHO`, `_TARGET_PE`, `_flags_reflect_rax`, 4
   peephole-tracker globals. Each was added without a
   corresponding update to main_cx.cyr.
3. Two dead `PF64BIN` / `PF64CMP` cx stubs collided with
   parse_expr.cyr's authoritative versions; v5.7.9's new
   duplicate-fn warning surfaced this when ANY consumer tried
   to build cx.
4. brk start was 5.5 MB but cx needed 39 MB to reach
   tok_types — silently failing alloc behavior on cx-only
   workloads.

Each breakage was found independently when somebody actually
tried to build cx for a downstream use. Fix at v5.7.11: the
DURABLE fix wasn't fixing the 4 issues — it was adding
`tests/regression-cx-build.sh` (gate 4u) so any future drift
fails CI immediately.

**Generalize**: BEFORE doing meaningful work on a backend or
infrequently-built tool, add the CI gate for it. Drift since
the last build IS what you're paying for in your slot —
account for it in the budget.

**The "orphaned path" inventory** (paths that get silent drift
without a gate):

- Each backend (`src/main_*.cyr`): cycc / cycc_aarch64 /
  cycc_win / cycc_macho_arm / cycc_cx. Each needs its own
  build-gate.
- Each cross-compiler output type: ELF, Mach-O, PE32+,
  cyrius-x bytecode. Each needs an output-gate (`xxd | grep`
  for known-bad byte patterns; readelf / otool / dumpbin for
  format validity).
- Each downstream consumer dep (sigil/mabda/yukti/etc.): each
  needs `cyrius soak` integration so a cyrius-side change
  that breaks them is caught before the downstream agent
  reports a regression.
- Each helper script (cyriusly / cyrius-init.sh /
  cyrius-port.sh): silent until a user runs it. Add a
  `--check` mode that exercises the script in CI.

**Anti-pattern**: assuming "if I'm not actively working on
backend X, it's still fine because last release shipped." It
ISN'T. The frontend evolves; backends silently rot.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `cx_drift_silent_accumulation_lesson`
+ v5.7.11 ship notes.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "anticipated_gotcha_pre_flight_v55x"
description = "Pre-flight gotcha bundles — record anticipated issues BEFORE starting an arc, not after. v5.5.3 (Win64 ABI) + v5.5.4 (native self-host) + v5.5.5+ (PE tail) shipped this way."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["scoping", "pre-flight", "v5.5.x"]
content = """
**The rule**: when an arc spans multiple slots and crosses
known-fragile territory (new platform, ABI change, large
refactor), record anticipated gotchas in a pre-flight doc
BEFORE starting. Not as predictions — as RUNNING NOTES that
the slot owner consults during the work and updates as
findings either confirm or refute each anticipation.

**The cyrius example** (v5.5.x platform-completion arc):

Before starting v5.5.3 (Win64 ABI), v5.5.4 (native self-host
on Win11), and v5.5.5+ (PE tail), the arc owner wrote
`v5_5_x_anticipated_gotchas` covering:

- Win64's caller-saves-XMM-args convention vs SysV's no-save
- Stack alignment requirement at CALL: rsp 16-byte aligned
  on SysV vs Win64 difference
- Win64's hidden RCX retptr for struct-return (vs SysV's RDI)
- Shadow space (Win64): callee gets 32 bytes of pre-allocated
  stack space caller MUST reserve
- PE32+ section layout: .text, .rdata, .data, .pdata, .reloc;
  each with its own alignment + RVA constraints
- LC_DYLD_INFO_ONLY (Mach-O): different from PE entirely;
  don't mix lessons

Some anticipated gotchas hit (shadow space caused 4 patches
in v5.5.4–v5.5.7); some didn't (RCX retptr was straightforward
once mapped). The pre-flight doc was the running journal that
captured each finding INLINE — not after the arc shipped, when
context is lost.

**Generalize**: write the pre-flight gotchas BEFORE the work,
update them DURING the work, archive them AFTER as field
notes. The discipline:

1. Brainstorm gotchas at arc-start (~30 min). Cover ABI,
   alignment, calling convention, error-code semantics, build-
   system diffs, test-runner diffs.
2. Each anticipated gotcha gets a 2-line entry: what + why-
   we-think-this-might-bite-us.
3. As work progresses, mark each as CONFIRMED (here's what
   bit) / REFUTED (turned out to be a non-issue) / OPEN
   (still ambiguous).
4. At arc closeout, the populated doc is the field-notes
   bundle — name it `v<arc>_x_gotchas_bundle`.

**Anti-pattern**: post-hoc retrospective that lists "what bit
us." Loses the prior-art context (what we DID anticipate vs
what surprised us). Pre-flight + update-in-place gives both.

Full backstory: v5_5.cyml's
`windows_arc_anticipated_gotchas` was the pre-flight doc,
v5_5.cyml's `v5_5_x_platform_rounding_gotchas` was the post-
arc bundle. Compare them — the diff is the arc's actual
surprise factor.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_dep_care_not_application_care"
description = "Any repo whose `dist/<name>.cyr` ships into cyrius `lib/` AND into downstream `lib/` via `cyrius deps` IS stdlib. Touching its public surface is the same severity as touching `lib/string.cyr` — full ecosystem-grep + major-bump-on-removal discipline, NOT application-style refactor-and-patch."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["process", "ecosystem", "semver", "stdlib", "v5.9.x"]
content = """
**The rule**: sigil, sakshi, agnosys, sankoch, niyama, sit, et al
ship `dist/<name>.cyr` bundles vendored into cyrius `lib/<name>.cyr`
AND into downstream consumer `lib/<name>.cyr` via `cyrius deps`.
That makes them stdlib dependencies, not applications. The
discipline transfer:

- **Public surface = every fn in the bundle that doesn't have a
  `_` prefix or explicit private convention.** "Internal by
  convention" doesn't mean private — if the symbol is reachable
  after `include "lib/<name>.cyr"`, it's API.
- **Symbol removal is a MAJOR version bump, never a patch.**
  Patches add fns, fix bugs, or rewrite internals while keeping
  public symbols stable. Removing a fn that was reachable
  yesterday is breaking, even if you "checked all the callers"
  inside the dep's own source tree.
- **"Checked all the callers" is a half-grep until it covers the
  ecosystem.** `grep -rn "<symbol>" /home/macro/Repos/` finds
  direct downstream callers. `find /home/macro/Repos -name
  "<dep>.cyr" -path "*/lib/*"` enumerates vendored copies. Both
  are mandatory before any public removal.
- **Snapshot + dist ping-pong is cross-repo.** Editing
  `cyrius/lib/<name>.cyr` requires same-version
  `~/.cyrius/.../lib/` refresh (per the
  `Snapshot-ping-pong-protection` CLAUDE.md pin). Editing
  `<dep>/dist/<name>.cyr` ALSO requires refold into
  `cyrius/lib/<name>.cyr` AND any downstream `<consumer>/lib/
  <name>.cyr` that pins the dep. Forgetting any side ships a
  partial change.

**Why — the sigil 3.0.2 incident (2026-05-06; cyrius v5.9.20
slot)**: Deleted `sigil/src/ct.cyr` to consolidate `ct_eq` /
`ct_eq_32` into cyrius stdlib's `lib/ct.cyr`. Justified as
"patch release — internal refactor only; sigil's API
unchanged." That framing was a category error:

1. `fn ct_eq(a, a_len, b, b_len)` was a PUBLIC symbol of sigil's
   bundle. Direct downstream callers grep'd post-hoc:
   `kavach` (1), `hoosh` (5), `libro` (9), `majra` (3) — none
   checked at slot entry. All would break when their sigil
   pin bumps to 3.0.2.
2. `ct_eq_32` "zero callers" claim was a half-grep of
   `sigil/src/*.cyr` only. Real callers in
   `sigil/programs/smoke.cyr` and `sigil/tests/bcyr/sigil.bcyr`
   — both of which the bundled tcyr/bcyr suite executes —
   caused immediate CI SIGILL. CI feedback loop took several
   round-trips to root-cause because each round patched
   downstream symptoms (missing tcyr includes, stale CI
   version pin) instead of admitting the fundamental
   stdlib-vs-application category error.
3. 17 sigil test/fuzz files included the deleted `src/ct.cyr`;
   9 tcyr files called bare `ct_eq` directly. None checked.
4. CI version pin `CYRIUS_VERSION=5.7.48` had been stale across
   multiple cyrius releases; the dep change required a
   v5.9.20+ bump that nobody surveyed.

The contrast with cyrius-side discipline was stark in the same
session: in cyrius the agent ran pre-delete grep,
snapshot-ping-pong protection, premise-check at slot entry,
full audit before bump, cross-arch propagation. In sigil the
agent deleted a file and labeled the changelog "internal
refactor."

**How to apply — checklist for any stdlib-dep change:**

Before editing the dep:
1. Identify the dep's public surface — every fn in `dist/<name>.cyr`
   without `_` prefix or `# private` annotation.
2. If the change removes or renames any public symbol:
   - Major version bump, OR a deprecation cycle with a compat
     shim that lets you keep a minor bump.
   - `grep -rn "<symbol>" /home/macro/Repos/` to find direct
     callers. Each is a downstream slot.
   - `find /home/macro/Repos -name "<dep>.cyr" -path "*/lib/*"`
     to enumerate vendored copies. Each is a future bump cost.
3. If the change is purely additive (new fn, no removal):
   - Patch / minor bump fine.
   - Still grep for collisions with downstream-defined names
     (consumers may have local fns with the same name; a
     stdlib add can shadow them).
4. Ecosystem premise-check at slot entry — same shape as
   `methodology.cyml::premise_check_at_slot_entry`, but
   spans every consumer repo, not just the cyrius source.
5. CI version pins in the dep's repo (and in every consumer
   repo) belong in the pre-ship checklist when the change
   depends on a specific upstream symbol.

**Anti-pattern to avoid**: "I'm just refactoring this repo
to use the new cyrius helper" — NO. If the repo is a stdlib
dep, refactoring its public surface IS publishing breaking
changes, regardless of whether the local-only callers were
the only call sites you happened to find. Ecosystem grep is
the gate, not local intuition.

**The smell**: when about to delete or rename a symbol in
ANY of: sigil, sakshi, agnosys, sankoch, niyama, sit, libro,
majra, kavach, hoosh — or any other repo with `dist/<name>.cyr`
vendored elsewhere — pause and ecosystem-grep first. Two
seconds saves a multi-round-trip CI hotfix loop and downstream
breakage rippled across 4+ consumer repos.

Cross-ref: `methodology.cyml::premise_check_at_slot_entry`
(the pin describes intended scope; the empirical state is
the actual scope). Memory pin
`feedback_stdlib_dep_discipline.md` carries the same rule
in the per-project memory layer.

Full backstory: cyrius CHANGELOG v5.9.20 entry (in flight),
sigil CHANGELOG 3.0.2 entry (in flight; pending recovery
decision: revert / compat-shim / major bump). The fact that
this incident happened in the same conversation that wrote
ecosystem-grep memory pins for v5.9.4 + v5.9.17 .sh-delete
incidents tells you the discipline transfer doesn't happen
automatically — it has to be EXPLICIT in vidya so an agent
searching "before deleting from sigil" hits it before the
first grep.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "real_flow_gate_vs_selfhost_placebo"
description = "Self-host (cycc==cycc) is a PLACEBO for whole classes of breakage — it reads source by path and never walks a dir, spawns a process, or resolves a dep. The actual test is a real consumer-flow gate (init → lib sync → deps → build → run) on real hardware. arm64-macOS lib sync rotted GREEN for 10+ releases behind self-host + hello-world smoke until a consumer hit it."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["process", "verification", "gate", "macho", "self-host", "found-by-ports", "v6.0.63"]
content = """
**The lesson**: a green self-host checkmark proves the compiler
reproduces ITS OWN bytes — nothing more. Self-host reads every
source by an explicit path; it NEVER:
  - walks a directory (getdents/getdirentries),
  - spawns a child process (fork/execve/waitpid),
  - resolves a dependency,
  - mkdir/unlink/chmod's the filesystem.
So an entire class of toolchain breakage ships GREEN behind it.
arm64-macOS `cyrius lib sync` (dir-walk) was broken for 10+
releases behind a green self-host + hello-world/exit-code smoke
— found by a consumer (yantra CI), the exact "found by ports"
failure CLAUDE.md forbids. The placebo wasn't ONE bad job; it
was trusting a checkmark whose mechanics can't reach the bug.

**The fix is a GATE, not a smarter checkmark**: run the flow a
consumer runs — `init → lib sync → deps → build an ALLOCATING
program → run/assert → reproducible` — go RED at the first
broken step, on real hardware, every release. The acceptance
test for the gate itself: the FIRST time it runs it must turn
the currently-broken platform red. If it's green on a
known-broken platform, the gate is lipstick, not a gate.
(scripts/funcgate-posix.sh + funcgate-win.ps1 + funcgate-stage.sh;
Windows can't run the wrapper at all — fork/execve/mkdir
undefined for PE — so its gate exercises cycc.exe compiling +
running allocating programs instead.)

**Three debugging corollaries, all earned in .63**:
1. "Works in a minimal probe, fails in the wrapper" → the
   WRAPPER (full include set) is the real test. Suspect a
   duplicate global bound by include order, not codegen — print
   the actual value of the global the failing path reads. (See
   gotchas: macho_syscall_number_dual_definition_61_vs_217.)
2. Verify on a host with NO ambient install. The gate first ran
   GREEN locally only because the machine's ~/.cyrius masked an
   init-detection miss; a clean host (pi) exposed it. An ambient
   install is a false-green generator — it answers the questions
   the gate is supposed to be asking.
3. A bug fix that turns a gate green can immediately surface the
   NEXT bug the broken step was hiding. Fixing macOS dir-walk got
   lib sync/deps/build/run green and THEN the reproducible step
   reded — a real, separate gate-harness bug (output-name
   embedding). Read each new red as progress, not regression.

Cross-ref: gotchas.cyml (macho_syscall_number_dual_definition_61_vs_217,
macho_output_basename_breaks_reproducible_cmp); retros/v60x.cyml;
CLAUDE.md Closeout 3b ("hello-world smoke is a placebo").
"""
